Copy the config folder to:



~/.config/conky/


---

â–¶ï¸ 3. Run Conky

To start it:



conky &



If it's configured properly, youâ€™ll see the widget appear on your desktop.


---

ğŸ” 4. Autostart Conky on Boot

If you want it running automatically every time you log in:

ğŸ’¾ Create an autostart entry



nano ~/.config/autostart/conky.desktop



Paste this:



[Desktop Entry]
Type=Application
Exec=conky -c ~/.config/conky/conky.conf
Hidden=false
NoDisplay=false
X-GNOME-Autostart-enabled=true
Name=Conky
Comment=System monitor


---

ğŸ§™ 5. Customize Your HUD

You can show all sorts of cool info like:

CPU/GPU temps

RAM, disk, network usage

Time & weather

Music playing

Hacker-style scrolling logs


Example config snippet:



conky.config = {
  background = true,
  use_xft = true,
  font = 'Fira Code:size=10',
  update_interval = 1,
  double_buffer = true,
  minimum_width = 200,
  alignment = 'top_right',
  gap_x = 10,
  gap_y = 30,
  own_window = true,
  own_window_type = 'desktop',
  own_window_argb_visual = true,
  own_window_argb_value = 120,
  own_window_transparent = true,
  own_window_hints = 'undecorated,below,sticky,skip_taskbar,skip_pager',
};

conky.text = [[
${time %A, %B %d %Y}
${time %H:%M:%S}
CPU: ${cpu}% ${cpubar 4}
RAM: $mem/$memmax ${membar 4}
Disk: ${fs_used /}/${fs_size /} ${fs_bar 4 /}
Net: ${downspeed wlp3s0} â†“â†‘ ${upspeed wlp3s0}
]];


